The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, June 10, 2004 				 Top guns in market scan
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, June 9: The finance ministry officials will hold a meeting with senior officials of the Reserve Bank and market regulator Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) on Friday to review financial markets.Officials expected to be present in the meeting include finance secretary D. C. Gupta, both the governor and deputy governor of the Reserve Bank of India and Sebi chairman G. N. Bajpai.																								This is a follow-up to the meeting held between Chidambaram and foreign investors, including bankers, last week.																								The meeting, to be held in Mumbai, will seek to boost confidence among foreign funds, which have dumped around $840 million worth of Indian stocks last month on fears for the future of reforms, after pumping in $4.3 billion in the first four months of 2004.																								The finance minister is friendly to the capital market and is aware of the need for new investments and consequently the importance of a stable and booming market, said sources.																								In addition to the selloff by foreign investors, which rattled investors and weighed heavily on stocks and the currency market, Merrill Lynch has cut its Indian stocks rating to market weight from overweight, saying investors should wait to see what the new leaders do.																								The meeting is also expected to bring measures to calm markets and spread the message that the government is committed to reforms and fiscal responsibility, the official said.																								Last month, the benchmark 30-share BSE index crashed 11 per cent to 4,505 points on May 17 on fears that economic reforms would slow down under the new Congress-led government and since then been swinging between 4,700-4,900 points.																								However, analysts say the market will really start responding after seeing the budget as this will clear doubts on the details of the common minimum programme  the economic policy blueprint  of the government. 																								There are fears that a huge spending plan on social services and infrastructure build-up might result in higher fiscal deficit, though the finance minister has said that such fears were unfounded.Sebi panel 																								The Securities Market Infrastructure Leveraging Expert (smile) panel constituted by Sebi today reviewed the process of primary market issues and procedures to simplify initial public offerings. The task force is headed by UTI Bank chief P. J. Nayak.
